     Bangladesh redrawing regional alliances
       </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
        <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
         <strong>
         Summary: Bangladesh is moving away from India to create a geopolitical shift in South Asia.</strong>
         </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
           Muhammad Yunus‚Äô move away from India to focus on China, Pakistan, and Turkey could harm Bangladesh‚Äôs <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-20-jun-25-analysis-h1-5-harm-bangladesh-s-long-term-independence" target="_blank">long-term independence</a>. His first major bilateral visit to China resulted in agreements on AI, defense technology, and granted duty-free market entry. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Yunus also reestablished ties with Turkey and Pakistan, ignoring ongoing public resentment from the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-20-jun-25-analysis-h1-6-1971-war" target="_blank">1971 war</a>. India, despite its past errors, remains Bangladesh‚Äôs key neighbor. Cutting long-standing ties could destabilize the border and the economy. A balanced, multipolar approach is essential for Bangladesh. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Some critics assert India‚Äôs backing of Hasina‚Äôs authoritarian rule and slow infrastructure funding contributed to the realignment of the agreement. Yunus‚Äôs China-leaning policy shift will risk autonomy and become a marginal player in China‚Äôs agenda. With elections approaching in April 2026, the future of this bold foreign policy remains uncertain. 
          </p>
         
        </mj-text>
